[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 9.9: Surgical Video Analysis
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research/Pilot · **Estimated Cost:** ~$2.50–$8.00 per procedure (processing only)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A surgeon performs a laparoscopic cholecystectomy. The camera records everything: 45 minutes of video showing instrument movements, tissue manipulation, anatomical landmarks appearing and disappearing behind smoke and blood. When the case is over, that video sits on a local drive in the OR. Nobody watches it unless something went wrong.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is a massive waste of information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Surgical video contains a dense record of what happened, when, and how. It captures technique, decision-making, complications, near-misses, and workflow efficiency in a way that no operative note ever could. An operative note says "the cystic duct was identified and clipped." The video shows the 90 seconds of careful dissection that preceded that clip, the moment of hesitation when the anatomy was unclear, and the subtle instrument repositioning that avoided a bile duct injury.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The problem is scale. A busy hospital generates thousands of hours of surgical video per year. No human can watch all of it. Quality improvement programs sample a handful of cases. Training programs review selected clips. Morbidity and mortality conferences look at cases after adverse events. The vast majority of surgical video is never analyzed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What if you could automatically understand what's happening in every frame? Identify which phase of the procedure is underway. Detect which instruments are in the field. Recognize critical anatomical structures. Flag moments where complications are developing. Build a searchable, structured index of every surgical case.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m That's surgical video analysis. It's one of the most computationally demanding problems in healthcare AI, and it's still largely in the research phase for clinical deployment. But the technology has matured enough that pilot implementations are realistic, and the potential impact on surgical quality, training, and safety is enormous.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: How Computers Understand Surgery
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Video Understanding: Beyond Single Frames
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Understanding surgical video is fundamentally different from analyzing a single medical image (like an X-ray or pathology slide). A single frame from a surgical video is often uninformative or ambiguous. You might see a metal instrument tip, some pink tissue, and a lot of smoke. Without temporal context (what came before, what comes after), even an expert surgeon might struggle to identify exactly what's happening.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Video understanding requires reasoning across time. The field has evolved through several generations:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Frame-level classification** was the earliest approach. Process each frame independently through an image classifier. This works for simple tasks (is an instrument visible? yes/no) but fails for anything requiring temporal context. You can't identify a surgical phase from a single frame because the same visual appearance might occur in multiple phases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal convolutional networks (TCNs)** process sequences of frame-level features. They apply 1D convolutions across time, capturing local temporal patterns. A TCN can learn that "grasper visible + cautery active + tissue retraction" sustained over 30 seconds likely indicates a dissection phase. TCNs are efficient and work well for phase recognition when the phases are relatively long and distinct.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recurrent architectures (LSTMs, GRUs)** maintain a hidden state that accumulates information over time. They're good at capturing long-range dependencies ("we're still in the same phase we entered 5 minutes ago") but struggle with very long sequences and can be expensive to train.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Transformer-based models** have become the state of the art for surgical video. Self-attention mechanisms can relate any frame to any other frame in the sequence, regardless of temporal distance. A transformer can learn that the current frame is related to something that happened 10 minutes ago (like a specific anatomical exposure that's now being referenced). The downside: transformers are computationally hungry, especially on long video sequences. Most practical implementations use a hierarchical approach: extract features at the frame level with a CNN, then process the feature sequence with a transformer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-task architectures** jointly predict multiple things: phase, instrument presence, anatomical structures, and actions. These tend to outperform single-task models because the tasks are correlated (certain instruments appear in certain phases, certain anatomy is visible during certain actions). Sharing representations across tasks provides implicit regularization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Core Tasks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Surgical video analysis encompasses several distinct recognition problems:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Phase recognition** identifies which stage of the procedure is currently underway. A laparoscopic cholecystectomy might have phases like: port placement, initial dissection, Calot's triangle dissection, clipping and cutting, gallbladder separation, extraction, and inspection. Phase recognition is the most mature task, with research models achieving 85-92% accuracy on benchmark datasets.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Instrument detection and tracking** identifies which surgical tools are visible in each frame and where they are. This is typically framed as object detection (bounding boxes around instruments) or instance segmentation (pixel-level masks). Challenges include occlusion (instruments behind tissue or smoke), motion blur, and the visual similarity between different instrument types.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Anatomy recognition** identifies critical anatomical structures. In cholecystectomy, this means the cystic duct, cystic artery, common bile duct, and hepatocystic triangle. This is arguably the highest-value task for safety: the most dangerous complication in cholecystectomy (bile duct injury) occurs when the surgeon misidentifies anatomy. A system that can reliably highlight the common bile duct could serve as a real-time safety check.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Action recognition** identifies what the surgeon is doing at a fine-grained level: grasping, cutting, clipping, cauterizing, retracting, irrigating. This combines instrument detection with motion analysis. It's useful for workflow analysis and training assessment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Event detection** identifies specific moments of clinical significance: bleeding events, instrument-tissue contact, clip placement, specimen extraction. These are the moments you'd want to index for later retrieval.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Makes This Genuinely Hard
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Surgical video analysis is one of the most challenging computer vision problems in healthcare. Here's why:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Visual complexity.** The surgical field is visually chaotic. Tissue colors are similar across structures. Smoke from cautery obscures the view. Blood pools and flows. Lighting changes as the camera moves. Specular reflections from wet tissue create bright spots that confuse detectors. The visual signal-to-noise ratio is far worse than, say, a chest X-ray.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal variability.** No two surgeries are identical. The same procedure performed by different surgeons, or by the same surgeon on different patients, will have different durations, different orderings of sub-steps, and different visual appearances. A phase recognition model trained on textbook-perfect cases will struggle with cases that deviate from the norm (which are exactly the cases you most want to analyze).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Annotation cost.** Training these models requires frame-level or segment-level annotations from expert surgeons. A single 45-minute video at 1 fps generates 2,700 frames that need labeling. At the phase level, this is manageable (annotate phase transitions). At the instrument or anatomy level, it requires bounding boxes or segmentation masks on individual frames. This is expensive, slow, and requires domain expertise that's in short supply.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real-time constraints.** If you want to provide intraoperative feedback (not just post-hoc analysis), you need inference latency under 100-200 milliseconds per frame. That's achievable for simple classification but challenging for multi-task models processing high-resolution video.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Generalization across procedures.** A model trained on cholecystectomy doesn't transfer to appendectomy. The phases are different, the instruments are different, the anatomy is different. Building a general surgical video understanding system requires training data across many procedure types, which multiplies the annotation cost.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Data volume.** A single procedure at 30 fps and 1080p resolution generates roughly 50-100 GB of raw video. Even at reduced frame rates (1-5 fps for analysis), you're dealing with substantial storage and compute requirements. A hospital performing 20 surgeries per day generates terabytes of video per month.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Is Today
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The honest assessment: surgical video analysis is at the boundary between research and early clinical deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Phase recognition** is the most mature. Several commercial products exist for specific procedures (primarily cholecystectomy and other laparoscopic procedures). Research accuracy on benchmark datasets (Cholec80, m2cai16) is in the 85-92% range. Clinical deployment is happening at a handful of academic centers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Instrument detection** is commercially available in some surgical platforms. The da Vinci robotic system, for example, has built-in instrument tracking. For standard laparoscopic video, research models achieve reasonable detection accuracy but struggle with occlusion and unusual instrument configurations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Anatomy recognition** is still primarily research-stage. The CholecSeg8k and other datasets have enabled progress, but clinical deployment requires higher accuracy than current models achieve, given the safety implications of misidentifying anatomy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real-time intraoperative feedback** is the holy grail and is not yet standard of care anywhere. A few research systems have demonstrated feasibility, but regulatory clearance, liability concerns, and workflow integration challenges remain significant barriers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For this recipe, we'll focus on a post-hoc analysis pipeline: processing recorded surgical video after the procedure for quality improvement, training, and research purposes. This sidesteps the real-time latency requirements and regulatory complexity of intraoperative systems while still delivering substantial value.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pipeline for surgical video analysis follows this conceptual flow:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Ingest Video] → [Preprocess / Sample Frames] → [Feature Extraction] → [Temporal Modeling] → [Multi-Task Prediction] → [Post-Processing] → [Structured Index] → [Query / Visualization]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Ingest Video.** Surgical video arrives from the OR recording system. This might be a direct feed from the laparoscopic camera, a recording from the surgical robot, or a capture from an overhead camera. The video needs to land in durable storage with metadata: procedure type, surgeon, date, patient identifier (de-identified for research use cases).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Preprocess / Sample Frames.** Raw surgical video at 30 fps is far more data than you need for most analysis tasks. Phase transitions happen over seconds, not milliseconds. Sampling at 1-5 fps is standard for phase recognition. For instrument detection, you might want higher rates (5-10 fps) to capture fast movements. Preprocessing also includes resizing, normalization, and optionally removing non-informative frames (black frames from camera disconnection, frames with no visible tissue).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feature Extraction.** Each sampled frame passes through a convolutional neural network (typically a ResNet-50 or similar backbone pretrained on ImageNet, then fine-tuned on surgical data) to produce a compact feature vector. This reduces each frame from millions of pixels to a few thousand numbers that encode the visual content. This step is the most computationally expensive per-frame operation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal Modeling.** The sequence of frame features passes through a temporal model (TCN, transformer, or hybrid) that reasons across time. This is where the system learns that "frame 1000 looks like dissection because frames 950-999 showed progressive tissue separation." The temporal model outputs per-frame predictions for each task.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-Task Prediction.** The temporal model produces predictions for multiple tasks simultaneously: current phase, instruments present, visible anatomy, ongoing action. Joint prediction improves accuracy because the tasks constrain each other (you don't see a clip applier during the initial dissection phase).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Post-Processing.** Raw per-frame predictions are noisy. A phase might flicker between "dissection" and "clipping" for a few frames at the boundary. Post-processing applies temporal smoothing (you can't change phase for just one frame), minimum duration constraints (a phase must last at least N seconds), and transition logic (certain phase sequences are impossible).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured Index.** The final output is a structured record of the procedure: a timeline of phases with start/end timestamps, instrument usage logs, anatomy visibility windows, and flagged events. This lives in a queryable database.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Query / Visualization.** Downstream consumers access the structured index through APIs or visualization tools. A surgeon reviewing their cases can jump to specific phases. A quality committee can search for all cases where a specific complication indicator was flagged. A training program can compile clips showing exemplary technique at a specific step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for video storage.** Surgical video files are large (50-100 GB per procedure at full resolution) and write-once. S3 provides durable, encrypted storage with lifecycle policies to manage cost. Use S3 Intelligent-Tiering or transition to S3 Glacier for videos older than 90 days that aren't actively being analyzed. S3's multipart upload handles the large file sizes gracefully.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Elemental MediaConvert for video preprocessing.** Before ML analysis, you need to transcode surgical video into a consistent format, extract frames at your target sample rate, and optionally generate lower-resolution proxy copies for faster processing. MediaConvert handles format normalization and frame extraction as a managed service, avoiding the need to run FFmpeg on EC2 instances.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for model training and batch inference.** Surgical video models require GPU compute for both training and inference. SageMaker provides managed training jobs with spot instance support (critical for the multi-day training runs these models require) and batch transform for processing video backlogs. For the feature extraction backbone, SageMaker's built-in support for PyTorch and distributed training across multiple GPUs is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions for pipeline orchestration.** The video analysis pipeline has multiple stages with dependencies, error handling requirements, and variable execution times. A single procedure might take 15-60 minutes to process depending on length. Step Functions manages the state machine: trigger on video upload, run preprocessing, launch inference, handle failures with retries, and write results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for the structured index.** Phase timelines, instrument logs, and event flags are time-series data with procedure-level access patterns. DynamoDB's flexible schema handles the varying output structures across procedure types, and its query performance supports the interactive visualization use case.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon OpenSearch Service for full-text and temporal search.** When a quality committee wants to find "all cholecystectomies where the critical view of safety was not clearly achieved" or "cases with bleeding events during Calot's triangle dissection," you need a search engine that can handle structured queries across the procedure index. OpenSearch supports both keyword search on annotations and range queries on timestamps.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon CloudWatch for monitoring.** Processing pipelines for surgical video are long-running and resource-intensive. CloudWatch metrics track processing latency, GPU utilization, inference failures, and queue depth. Alarms catch stuck pipelines before the backlog grows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[🎥 OR Recording System] -->|Upload| B[S3 Bucket\nsurgical-video-raw/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|S3 Event| C[Step Functions\nvideo-analysis-pipeline]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Transcode + Extract Frames| D[MediaConvert]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Frames at 1-5 fps| E[S3 Bucket\nsurgical-frames/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Batch Transform| F[SageMaker\nFeature Extraction\n+ Temporal Model]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|Predictions| G[Lambda\nPost-Processing]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Structured Results| H[DynamoDB\nprocedure-index]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Searchable Index| I[OpenSearch\nprocedure-search]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H --> J[API Gateway\nQuery API]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I --> J
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J --> K[📊 Visualization Dashboard]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style H fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style I fill:#9cf,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon S3, AWS Elemental MediaConvert, Amazon SageMaker, AWS Step Functions, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon OpenSearch Service, AWS Lambda, Amazon API Gateway, Amazon CloudWatch |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `mediaconvert:CreateJob`, `sagemaker:CreateTransformJob`, `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:Query`, `es:ESHttpPost`, `es:ESHttpGet`, `states:StartExecution` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (surgical video is PHI; even de-identified video may contain identifiable features) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for all buckets; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; OpenSearch: encryption at rest and node-to-node encryption; all transit over TLS; SageMaker: volume encryption on training and inference instances |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: SageMaker, OpenSearch, and Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, and CloudWatch Logs. OpenSearch domain must be VPC-only (no public endpoint for PHI data). |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all S3, SageMaker, and DynamoDB API calls for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **GPU Instances** | SageMaker training: ml.p3.2xlarge or ml.g5.2xlarge minimum. Batch inference: ml.g5.xlarge. Budget for multi-day training runs. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Public surgical video datasets: Cholec80 (80 cholecystectomy videos with phase annotations), m2cai16 (tool and phase annotations), CholecSeg8k (semantic segmentation). These are research datasets; never use real patient video without IRB approval and proper de-identification. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Processing: ~$2.50-$8.00 per procedure (MediaConvert + SageMaker inference). Training: ~$500-$2,000 per model training run (multi-day GPU). Storage: ~$1-2/month per procedure (S3 Intelligent-Tiering). OpenSearch: ~$200-500/month for a small domain. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores raw surgical video and extracted frames; lifecycle policies manage cost |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Elemental MediaConvert** | Transcodes video to consistent format; extracts frames at target sample rate |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Trains video analysis models (GPU); runs batch inference on new procedures |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates the multi-stage pipeline with error handling and retries |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores structured procedure index (phases, instruments, events) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon OpenSearch Service** | Enables search across procedure annotations and temporal queries |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Post-processing logic, API handlers, pipeline glue |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon API Gateway** | REST API for querying procedure index and search |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitoring, metrics, and alarms for pipeline health |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data stores |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Video ingestion and metadata registration.** When a surgical video arrives from the OR recording system, the pipeline registers it with metadata (procedure type, date, surgeon identifier, duration) and triggers processing. The video lands in an encrypted S3 bucket, and an S3 event notification kicks off the Step Functions state machine. This separation between storage and processing is important: if the analysis pipeline is down or backed up, videos still land safely and get processed when capacity is available. Skip this step (process inline during upload) and you risk losing video data if the processing pipeline fails.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION ingest_video(video_file, metadata):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Generate a unique identifier for this procedure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This ID links the raw video, extracted frames, and analysis results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     procedure_id = generate unique ID (e.g., UUID)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Upload the video to encrypted storage.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Surgical video files are large (50-100 GB), so use multipart upload.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     upload video_file to S3 bucket "surgical-video-raw/"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         with key: "{procedure_id}/raw_video.mp4"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         with encryption: SSE-KMS
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         with metadata: procedure_type, surgeon_id, procedure_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Register the procedure in the tracking database.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Status starts as "ingested" and progresses through the pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write to DynamoDB table "procedure-registry":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         procedure_id    = procedure_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         status          = "ingested"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         procedure_type  = metadata.procedure_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         surgeon_id      = metadata.surgeon_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         procedure_date  = metadata.procedure_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         video_duration  = metadata.duration_seconds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ingested_at     = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Trigger the analysis pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     start Step Functions execution with input:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         procedure_id = procedure_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         video_key    = "{procedure_id}/raw_video.mp4"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         procedure_type = metadata.procedure_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN procedure_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Frame extraction and preprocessing.** Raw surgical video at 30 fps contains far more temporal redundancy than the analysis models need. Phase transitions happen over seconds, not frames. This step extracts frames at a configurable sample rate (typically 1 fps for phase recognition, up to 5 fps for instrument detection), resizes them to the model's expected input resolution, and filters out non-informative frames (black frames from camera disconnection, completely obscured frames from lens fogging). The output is a sequence of clean, consistently-sized frames ready for feature extraction. Skip this step and you'll burn 30x more GPU compute on redundant frames with no accuracy improvement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION extract_frames(procedure_id, video_key, sample_rate_fps):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Use a managed transcoding service to extract frames.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This avoids running FFmpeg on EC2 and handles format inconsistencies
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // across different OR recording systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     create MediaConvert job:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         input:  S3 object at video_key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         output: S3 bucket "surgical-frames/{procedure_id}/"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         settings:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             frame_rate: sample_rate_fps        // typically 1-5 fps
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             output_format: JPEG                // individual frame images
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             resolution: 224x224 or 384x384     // match model input size
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Some OR systems record in unusual formats or codecs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // MediaConvert normalizes these automatically.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Wait for the transcoding job to complete.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // A 45-minute video at 1 fps produces ~2,700 frames.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     wait for job completion (poll or use EventBridge)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Filter out non-informative frames.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Black frames occur when the camera is disconnected or the light source is off.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Completely white/washed-out frames occur from lens fogging or direct light.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     frame_list = list all frames in "surgical-frames/{procedure_id}/"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     valid_frames = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each frame in frame_list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         pixel_stats = compute mean and standard deviation of pixel values
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF pixel_stats.mean < 10:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             SKIP  // black frame (camera off or disconnected)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF pixel_stats.std < 5:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             SKIP  // uniform frame (lens cap, complete fog, or saturation)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append frame to valid_frames
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write the valid frame manifest for downstream processing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write valid_frames list to S3: "surgical-frames/{procedure_id}/manifest.json"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN count of valid_frames
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Feature extraction.** Each valid frame passes through a convolutional neural network (the "backbone") that compresses the visual information into a compact feature vector. Think of this as translating each frame from "millions of pixel values" into "a few thousand numbers that capture what's visually important." The backbone is typically a ResNet-50 or similar architecture pretrained on ImageNet (general image recognition) and then fine-tuned on surgical video data. Fine-tuning is critical: a model trained only on natural images doesn't understand that "pink tissue with a metal instrument" is the normal state of affairs in surgery. This step is the most GPU-intensive per-frame operation, but it only needs to run once per frame. The extracted features are cached for use by multiple downstream models.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION extract_features(procedure_id, frame_manifest):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load the fine-tuned feature extraction model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This is a CNN backbone (e.g., ResNet-50) trained on surgical video.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The final classification layer is removed; we want the feature vector,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // not a class prediction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     model = load pretrained surgical feature extractor
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features = empty list (will hold one feature vector per frame)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Process frames in batches for GPU efficiency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Batch size depends on GPU memory; 32-64 frames per batch is typical.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each batch of frames from frame_manifest:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Load frame images and normalize pixel values.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Normalization uses the same mean/std as the training data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         images = load and normalize batch of frame images from S3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Forward pass through the CNN backbone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Output shape: [batch_size, feature_dim] where feature_dim is typically 2048.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         batch_features = model.forward(images)  // GPU operation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append batch_features to features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Save the feature sequence to S3 for temporal modeling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This is much smaller than the raw frames: ~8 KB per frame vs. ~150 KB per frame.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     save features array to S3: "surgical-features/{procedure_id}/features.npy"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN feature array shape (num_frames, feature_dim)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Temporal modeling and multi-task prediction.** This is where the system reasons across time. The sequence of frame features (from Step 3) passes through a temporal model that considers the full context of the procedure to make predictions at each time point. A transformer-based architecture attends to all frames simultaneously, learning patterns like "this visual pattern following that visual pattern usually means we're transitioning from dissection to clipping." The model outputs predictions for multiple tasks: surgical phase, instrument presence, and (if trained for it) anatomy visibility. Joint prediction helps because the tasks constrain each other. You wouldn't expect to see a clip applier during the initial port placement phase. Skip this step and use only frame-level predictions, and you'll get noisy, temporally inconsistent results that flicker between phases every few frames.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION temporal_prediction(procedure_id, features):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load the temporal model (transformer or TCN).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This model was trained on annotated surgical video sequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // It takes a sequence of frame features and outputs per-frame predictions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     temporal_model = load trained temporal model for procedure_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Run inference on the full feature sequence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Input shape: [1, num_frames, feature_dim]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Output: per-frame predictions for each task
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     predictions = temporal_model.forward(features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // predictions contains:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   phase_logits:      [num_frames, num_phases]       - probability of each phase per frame
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   instrument_logits: [num_frames, num_instruments]  - probability of each instrument per frame
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   event_logits:      [num_frames, num_event_types]  - probability of each event type per frame
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Convert logits to probabilities and class predictions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     phase_predictions = argmax(softmax(predictions.phase_logits), axis=1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     phase_confidences = max(softmax(predictions.phase_logits), axis=1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     instrument_predictions = sigmoid(predictions.instrument_logits) > 0.5  // multi-label
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     instrument_confidences = sigmoid(predictions.instrument_logits)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     event_predictions = sigmoid(predictions.event_logits) > 0.3  // lower threshold for events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     event_confidences = sigmoid(predictions.event_logits)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phases: phase_predictions with confidences,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         instruments: instrument_predictions with confidences,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         events: event_predictions with confidences,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         frame_timestamps: computed from frame indices and sample_rate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Temporal post-processing.** Raw per-frame predictions from the temporal model are still noisy at phase boundaries. A phase might flicker for a few frames, or a brief instrument occlusion might cause a false "instrument absent" prediction. Post-processing applies domain knowledge to clean up the predictions: minimum phase duration constraints (a surgical phase can't last 2 seconds), transition smoothing (median filtering over a window), and impossible transition elimination (you can't go from "extraction" back to "initial dissection"). This step dramatically improves the usability of the output. Without it, the phase timeline would have dozens of spurious micro-transitions that make no surgical sense.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION post_process(raw_predictions, sample_rate_fps):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Phase smoothing ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply median filter to remove single-frame phase flickers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Window size of 15 frames at 1 fps = 15 seconds of smoothing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     smoothed_phases = median_filter(raw_predictions.phases, window=15)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Enforce minimum phase duration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // No surgical phase lasts less than 30 seconds in practice.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     MIN_PHASE_DURATION = 30 * sample_rate_fps  // 30 seconds worth of frames
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     segments = identify contiguous segments of same phase in smoothed_phases
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each segment in segments:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF segment.duration < MIN_PHASE_DURATION:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Merge this short segment into the surrounding phase.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Use the phase of the longer neighbor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             merge segment into longer adjacent segment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Instrument smoothing ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Brief instrument disappearances (< 3 seconds) are likely occlusion, not removal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each instrument_type:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         fill gaps shorter than 3 * sample_rate_fps frames
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Build phase timeline ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     phase_timeline = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each contiguous phase segment:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append to phase_timeline: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             phase_name:  segment.phase_label,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             start_time:  segment.start_frame / sample_rate_fps,  // seconds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             end_time:    segment.end_frame / sample_rate_fps,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             duration:    (segment.end_frame - segment.start_frame) / sample_rate_fps,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             confidence:  mean confidence of frames in segment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Build event list ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     events = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each detected event:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append to events: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             event_type:  event.label,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             timestamp:   event.frame / sample_rate_fps,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             confidence:  event.confidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             context:     surrounding phase at that timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phase_timeline: phase_timeline,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         instrument_log: instrument presence intervals,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         events: events,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_duration: total frames / sample_rate_fps
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 6: Store structured index and enable search.** The post-processed results become a structured, queryable record of the procedure. This step writes the phase timeline, instrument usage, and events to both a fast-lookup store (DynamoDB for procedure-level queries) and a search index (OpenSearch for cross-procedure queries). The dual-write pattern serves different access patterns: "show me the timeline for procedure X" hits DynamoDB; "find all procedures where bleeding occurred during Calot's triangle dissection" hits OpenSearch. Skip the search index and you lose the ability to do population-level quality analysis, which is half the value of automated video analysis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION store_results(procedure_id, analysis_results):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write the full procedure analysis to DynamoDB.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This supports fast lookup by procedure_id.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write to DynamoDB table "procedure-index":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         procedure_id    = procedure_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         status          = "analyzed"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         analyzed_at     = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phase_timeline  = analysis_results.phase_timeline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         instrument_log  = analysis_results.instrument_log
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         events          = analysis_results.events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_duration  = analysis_results.total_duration
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model_version   = current model version identifier
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Index in OpenSearch for cross-procedure search.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Flatten the timeline into searchable documents.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each phase in analysis_results.phase_timeline:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         index in OpenSearch "procedure-phases":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             procedure_id  = procedure_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             phase_name    = phase.phase_name
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             start_time    = phase.start_time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             end_time      = phase.end_time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             duration      = phase.duration
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             confidence    = phase.confidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             procedure_type = metadata.procedure_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             surgeon_id    = metadata.surgeon_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             procedure_date = metadata.procedure_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each event in analysis_results.events:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         index in OpenSearch "procedure-events":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             procedure_id  = procedure_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             event_type    = event.event_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             timestamp     = event.timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             confidence    = event.confidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             phase_context = event.context
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             procedure_type = metadata.procedure_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             surgeon_id    = metadata.surgeon_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Update the procedure registry status.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     update DynamoDB "procedure-registry" where procedure_id:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         status = "complete"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         completed_at = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN success
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter09.09-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample output for a laparoscopic cholecystectomy:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "procedure_id": "proc-2026-05-15-a8f3c",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "procedure_type": "laparoscopic_cholecystectomy",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "total_duration_seconds": 2847,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "phase_timeline": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "phase_name": "port_placement",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "start_time": 0,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "end_time": 185,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "duration": 185,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "confidence": 0.94
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "phase_name": "initial_dissection",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "start_time": 185,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "end_time": 612,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "duration": 427,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "confidence": 0.91
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "phase_name": "calot_triangle_dissection",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "start_time": 612,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "end_time": 1340,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "duration": 728,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "confidence": 0.87
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "phase_name": "clipping_and_cutting",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "start_time": 1340,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "end_time": 1523,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "duration": 183,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "confidence": 0.93
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
